DNS 
    WHAT IS DNS AND ITS ROLE IN NETWORKING?
        - DNS (Domain Name System) is a system that translates human-readable domain names (like google.com) into IP addresses that computers use to identify each other on a network.
        - Its main role is to make the internet easier to use, so users don’t have to remember numerical IP addresses.
        - When a user enters a website, DNS queries a server to find the correct IP address and directs the request to the right         destination.
        - It works alongside protocols like IP to ensure data is sent to the correct device.
        - Overall, DNS acts like a “phonebook of the internet,” enabling fast and efficient communication between devices
    DNS COMPONENTS?
        - DNS components overview: The DNS is made up of several parts that work together to translate domain names into IP addresses. Key components include resolvers (client-side request handlers), name servers (which store DNS records), and zone files (which contain the actual mappings).
        - Name servers (what they are): Name servers are specialized servers that store and provide DNS records for domains. They answer queries about domain names by returning the corresponding IP address or other related information.
        - How name servers work: When a user enters a domain, a DNS resolver sends a query through a hierarchy of name servers. This typically involves root servers, top-level domain (TLD) servers (like .com or .org), and authoritative name servers. The authoritative server holds the final answer and responds with the correct IP address.
        - Zone files (what they are): Zone files are text-based files stored on authoritative name servers. They contain DNS records that define how a domain should be resolved.
        - What zone files include: These files store records such as A records (mapping domain names to IP addresses), CNAME records (aliases), MX records (mail servers), and NS records (which define the authoritative name servers for the domain).
        - Overall role: Name servers use the information in zone files to respond to DNS queries quickly and accurately, enabling users to access websites without needing to know IP addresses.
DNS RECORDS?
    - DNS records are instructions stored on DNS servers that tell the internet how to handle requests for a domain, such as where to find its website or email service. For example, an A record links a domain to an IP address, a CNAME creates an alias to another domain, an MX record directs email to mail servers, and a TXT record stores verification or security information. Together, these records allow DNS to translate human-friendly domain names into the technical details needed for devices to communicate.

     +--------+----------------------+------------------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------+
| Type   | Name (Host)          | Value / Points To            | Description                                                  |
+--------+----------------------+------------------------------+--------------------------------------------------------------+
| A      | example.com          | 93.184.216.34                | Maps a domain name to an IPv4 address (used for websites)    |
| AAAA   | example.com          | 2001:db8::1                  | Maps a domain name to an IPv6 address                        |
| CNAME  | www                  | example.com                  | Creates an alias from one domain to another                  |
| MX     | example.com          | mail.example.com (prio 10)   | Specifies mail server responsible for receiving emails       |
